When we investigate the mechanism of the electrochemical oxidation of SER at MIP/GQDs/2D-hBN/GCE, the relationship between anodic potential and pH was obtained as Epa = 0.4818–0.05807 pH for SER. The value of slope is close to the theoretical value of -0.059 mV/pH. Thus, the numbers of electron and proton on electrochemical oxidation are equal (Scheme 2
                           ). According to DPV signals of SER in the range of pH 6.0–8.0, they increased up to pH 7.0 (Fig. 4
                           A). After pH 7.0, the signals diminished or remained constant. Thus, pH 7.0 was selected as the optimum pH for subsequent experiments [24].

Fig. 5
 indicated the relation between current signals and SER concentrations at MIP/GQDs/2D-hBN/GCE (from 1.0 × 10−12 M to 1.0 × 10−8 M). The regression equations are y (µA) = 29.819x (nM) + 0.1524 for MIP and y (µA) = 0.6016x (nM) − 0.0124 for NIP. According to the results of MIP and NIP, the reliability of the measurements was confirmed. Thus, MIP electrode in this article shows more response to SER analyte (inset of Fig. 5). The quantification limit (LOQ) and LOD for SER were obtained as 1.0 × 10−12 M and 2.0 × 10−13 M, respectively. The comparisons between the prepared MIP sensor and the reported systems were made (Table 1
). The MIP/GQDs/2D-hBN/GCE presents the more sensitive analysis results with high selectivity.

The selectivity tests were done in SER, DOP, TRY and NOR (Scheme 3
                        ). MIP/GQDs/2D-hBN/GCE was 5.0, 10.0 and 20.0 times selective towards SER in comparison with DOP, TRY and NOR (Fig. 6
                        ). Thus, we can say that the molecular imprinting technique provides high selectivity for SER detection. For the stability of MIP/GQDs/2D-hBN/GCE, the signals of 1.0 nM SER on MIP/GQDs/2D-hBN/GCE were measured for 60 days and repeated signals at about 10.0 µA were obtained. Hence, the developed nanosensor has high stability in real sample analysis. For repeatability test of MIP/GQDs/2D-hBN/GCE in the presence of 1.0 nM SER, 25 differential pulse voltammograms were taken and the repeated signals were obtained. The reproducibility test was performed with ten different MIP/GQDs/2D-hBN modified electrodes. These imprinted electrodes were fabricated independently by the same procedure. The value of relative standard deviation is 0.73% for current signal in presence of 1.0 nM SER. This situation indicates the reliability of the sensor preparation procedure. Finally, the reusability of MIP/GQDs/2D-hBN modified electrode was investigated. According to the results, MIP/GQDs/2D-hBN modified electrode is not a disposable sensor. It can be used at least 20 times by washing with 0.1 M PBS (pH 7.0).
